eptions of Islamic theology and practice as well as Muslim and British interactions dating back to the colonial period to explain the resurgence of shari'ah, with implications for Muslim-majority countries around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aIslam and politicszNigeria, Northern. 0aIslam and statezNigeria, Northern. 0aIslamic courtszNigeria, Northern. 0aIslamic lawzNigeria, Northern. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh  a1990s.  aafrica.  aafrican history.  aafrican.  acolonial period.  acolonialism.  adeath penalty.  adeath sentence.  afeminism.  afeminist studies.  afeminist.  agender equality.  agender inequality.  aislam.  aislamic.  ajournalism.  amuslim.  anigeria.  anigerian history.  anigerian.  apublic execution.  apublic stoning.  asensationalism.  asexual misconduct.  asexual violence.  ashariah law.  astoning.  atheology.  atrial.  awestern world.  awomens issues.  awomens rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029377940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520967144423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520967144/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles